Killer Tip: Program Manager

Problem: Despite its improved interface, Windows still adheres to DOS's
eight-character file-naming convention: It looks nice, but results in
forgettable filenames.

Solution: Generate icons for the files you access frequently. In Program
Manager, select File, New, and select Group. Name the new group
Documents. While the Documents group window is open, select File, New,
Program Item. After Description, type up to 40 characters, such as "Lunch
room lighting proposal to John." After the command line prompt, type the
filename--for example, lnchlit.doc, a Word for Windows document--and
after Working Directory, enter the directory where that file is stored.
Assign an icon by clicking the Change Icon button and running through the
treasure trove of icons, and you're done. When you double-click on this
icon, it should launch Word for Windows and bring up the document. If you
get an error message saying "No application is associated with the file,"
go into File Manager, select the file, and execute File, Associate, then
select an application to run with this file.

